    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:r-to-l"/><persName><name key="Συνήνιτος">Συνήνιτος</name></persName> τόδε
                    <lb n="2" style="text-direction:l-to-r"/>ὁ <persName><name type="partonymic" key="Εὐκλώτας">Εὐκλώτα</name></persName>.
                </ab></div>
            
            <div type="translation">
                <p>
                    Synenitus, son of Euklotas, (took) this.
                </p></div>
            
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Follows Hoffmann with inspecting the item. The mitra was part of a full armor (cf. NY.NY.MMA.G.1989.281.49), and three other mitrae were found at Afrati, Crete. 
                    The text is written boustrophedon, “plough-fashion,” when each line is written in the reverse direction than the previous line, common in 7th-6th c. BCE Greece.   </p></div>
            
            
